[[File:Chorus electromagnetic palmer 2003-02-27 T085030.png|thumb|[[Very low frequency|VLF]] [[spectrogram]] of electromagnetic chorus, as received by the [[Stanford University]] VLF group's wave receiver at [[Palmer Station]], [[Antarctica]]. The chorus can be seen between 1000 Hz and 3000 Hz, sandwiched between components of [[radio atmospheric|sferics]]]]
The [[electromagnetism|electromagnetic]] '''dawn chorus''' is a phenomenon that occurs most often at or shortly after [[dawn]] local time. With the proper [[radio]] equipment, dawn chorus can be converted to sounds that resemble [[dawn chorus (birds)|birds' dawn chorus]] (by coincidence).
The electromagnetic dawn chorus is believed to be generated by a [[Doppler effect|Doppler-shifted]] [[Electron cyclotron resonance|cyclotron interaction]] between anisotropic distributions of energetic (> 40 keV) electrons and ambient background VLF noise. These energetic electrons are generally injected into the inner magnetosphere at the onset of the substorm expansion phase.<ref> {{Cite journal | last1 = Nunn | first1 = D. | last2 = Omura | first2 = Y. | last3 = Matsumoto | first3 = H. | last4 = Nagano | first4 = I. | last5 = Yagitani | first5 = S. | title = The numerical simulation of VLF chorus and discrete emissions observed on the Geotail satellite using a Vlasov code | journal = J. Geophys. Res. | volume = 102 | pages = 27083–27098 | year = 1997 | doi = 10.1029/97JA02518|bibcode = 1997JGR...10227083N }} </ref><ref> {{Cite journal | last1 = Trakhtengerts | first1 = V. Y. | title = A generation mechanism for chorus emission | journal = Ann. Geophys. | volume = 17 | pages = 95–100 | year = 1999 | doi = 10.1007/s00585-999-0095-4|bibcode = 1999AnGeo..17...95T }} </ref> Dawn choruses occur more frequently during [[Geomagnetic storm|magnetic storms]].
This phenomenon also occurs during [[auroral light|aurorae]], when it is termed an [[auroral chorus]].
==See also== *[[Auroral chorus]] *[[Hiss (electromagnetic)]] *[[Whistler (radio)]] *[[Cluster One]], a [[Pink Floyd]] track using [[Radio atmospheric|sferics]] and dawn chorus as an overture
