{{Infobox power station | name = Dublin Waste-to-Energy Facility | name_official = | image = Dublin Waste-to-Energy Facility.jpg | image_size = 230 | image_alt = | image_caption = The Dublin Waste-to-Energy Facility | location_map = Ireland | location_map_size = | location_map_caption= | coordinates = {{Coord|53.341915|-6.200809}} | country = [[Ireland]] | location = [[Poolbeg]], [[Dublin]] | status = O | construction_began = 2014 | commissioned = 2017 | decommissioned = | cost = €600m | owner = [[ Covanta Energy]] | operator = [[Covanta Energy]] | th_fuel_primary = [[Municipal solid waste]] (MSW) | th_fuel_tertiary = | ps_units_operational= | ps_units_manu_model = | th_cogeneration = | th_combined_cycle = | ps_electrical_capacity= 60 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac= | website = | extra = }} The '''Dublin Waste-to-Energy Facility''', also known as the '''Poolbeg Incinerator''',<ref>{{cite web|title=Poolbeg incinerator takes its first delivery of rubbish |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/poolbeg-incinerator-takes-its-first-delivery-of-rubbish-1.3059217|journal=[[The Irish Times]]|author= Vivienne Clarke, Olivia Kelly|date=April 24, 2017}}</ref> is a [[waste-to-energy plant]] serving the [[Greater Dublin Area]], located on the [[Poolbeg|Poolbeg peninsula]]. The plant is capable of producing up to 60 [[megawatts]] of electricity, enough to power 80,000 homes, and provide [[district heating]] for up to 50,000 homes in the Dublin area.<ref>{{cite web|title=An ‘under the hood’ look at Dublin’s First ‘waste-to-energy’ plant|url=https://seanduke.com/2016/08/09/an-under-the-hood-look-at-dublins-first-waste-to-energy-plant/|journal=Science Spinning|author=Sean Duke|date=August 9, 2016}}</ref> The facility will process up to 600,000 tonnes of waste per year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Covanta’s Dublin, Ireland, WTE Facility Receives First Waste Delivery|url=http://www.waste360.com/waste-energy/covanta-s-dublin-ireland-wte-facility-receives-first-waste-delivery|journal=Waste360|author=|date=April 24, 2017}}</ref> Poolbeg accepted its first delivery of waste on the 24th of April 2017.<ref>[http://www.thejournal.ie/poolbeg-first-delivery-3355256-Apr2017/ Daragh Brophy. "The controversial Poolbeg incinerator has taken its first delivery of waste". April 24, 2017. TheJournal.ie]</ref>
The proposal to build an incinerator at this location provoked controversy since its inception in 1997 with concerns about [[traffic]] and [[Air pollution|emissions]], but construction work finally started in 2014.
==Incidents== On June 8, 2017, eleven people were hospitalised after an ‘uncontrolled release’ of [[Lime (material)|lime]] inside the flue gas treatment area inside the plant.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eleven hospitalised after incident at Dublin’s Poolbeg incinerator|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/eleven-hospitalised-after-incident-at-dublin-s-poolbeg-incinerator-1.3112097|journal=[[The Irish Times]]|author=Sarah Burns, Jack Power|date=June 8, 2017}}</ref> Covanta, the operator of the plant, was ordered to temporarily cease the incineration process at the facility by the [[Health and Safety Authority]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Poolbeg operators told to temporarily cease incineration|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2017/0609/881596-poolbeg-incineration-order/|journal=[[RTÉ News and Current Affairs|RTÉ News]]|author=|date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>
