{{short description|US hydrologic region}} {{Infobox river | name = New England water resource region | name_native = | name_native_lang = | name_other = | name_etymology = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | map = HUC01.jpg | map_size = 250 | map_caption = The New England region, with its 11 4-digit sub-region hydrologic unit boundaries. | map_alt = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_map_size = | pushpin_map_caption= | pushpin_map_alt = | subdivision_type1 = Countries | subdivision_name1 = [[Canada]], [[United States]] | subdivision_type2 = States | subdivision_name2 = Includes all of [[Maine]], [[New Hampshire]] and [[Rhode Island]], and parts of [[Connecticut]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Vermont]] | subdivision_type3 = | subdivision_name3 = | subdivision_type4 = | subdivision_name4 = | subdivision_type5 = | subdivision_name5 = <!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS --> | length = | width_min = | width_avg = | width_max = | depth_min = | depth_avg = | depth_max = | discharge1_location= | discharge1_min = | discharge1_avg = | discharge1_max = <!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES --> | source1 = | source1_location = | source1_coordinates= <!-- {{Coord|...}} --> | source1_elevation = | mouth = | mouth_location = | mouth_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|...|display=inline,title}} --> | mouth_elevation = | progression = | river_system = | basin_size = {{convert|73,753|sqmi|km2|abbr=on}} | basin_landmarks = | basin_population = | tributaries_left = | tributaries_right = | waterbodies = | waterfalls = | bridges = | ports = | custom_label = | custom_data = | extra = }}
The '''New England water resource region''' is one of 21 major geographic areas, or [[Water resource region|regions]], in the first level of classification used by the [[United States Geological Survey]] to divide and sub-divide the [[United States]] into successively smaller [[hydrologic unit]]s. These geographic areas contain either the drainage area of a major river, or the combined drainage areas of a series of rivers.<ref name=USGS_WS>{{cite web|title=Science in Your Watershed - Locate Your Watershed|url=http://water.usgs.gov/wsc/watershed_finder.html|publisher=[[USGS]]|accessdate=2016-10-12}} {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name=USGS_HUC>{{cite web|title=Hydrologic Unit Maps|url=http://water.usgs.gov/GIS/huc.html|publisher=[[USGS]]|accessdate=2016-10-12}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> The New England region, which is listed with a 2-digit hydrologic unit code (HUC) of 01, has an approximate size of {{convert|73,753|sqmi|km2|abbr=off|lk=on|sp=us}}, and consists of 11 sub-regions, which are listed with the 4-digit HUCs 0101 through 0111.
This region includes the drainage within the United States that ultimately discharges into: (a) the [[Bay of Fundy]]; (b) the [[Atlantic Ocean]] within and between the states of [[Maine]] and [[Connecticut]]; (c) [[Long Island Sound]] north of the [[New York (state)|New York]]-[[Connecticut]] state line; and (d) the [[Saint-François River|Riviere St. Francois]], a tributary of the [[Saint Lawrence River]]. Includes all of [[Maine]], [[New Hampshire]] and [[Rhode Island]], and parts of [[Connecticut]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Vermont]].<ref name=USGS_HUC_name>{{cite web|title=Boundary Descriptions and Names of Regions, Subregions, Accounting Units and Cataloging Units|url=https://water.usgs.gov/GIS/huc_name.html|publisher=[[USGS]]|accessdate=2016-10-12}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>
[[Image:HUC01.jpg|frame|center|The New England region, with its 11 4-digit sub-region hydrologic unit boundaries.]]
