{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}
{{short description|A fluid layer composed of mostly iron and nickel between Earth's solid inner core and its mantle}}
{{For|the cores of other planetary bodies|Planetary core}}
{{broader|Earth core}}
[[File:Earth poster.svg|upright=1.35|thumb|The internal structure of Earth]]

The '''outer core''' of the Earth is a fluid layer about {{convert|2400|km|mi|abbr=on}} thick and composed of mostly [[iron]] and [[nickel]] that lies above Earth's solid [[inner core]] and below its [[mantle (geology)|mantle]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Earth's Interior |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/science/earth/surface-of-the-earth/earths-interior/ |website=Science & Innovation |publisher=National Geographic |accessdate=14 November 2018 |date=18 January 2017}}</ref> Its outer boundary lies {{convert|2890|km|mi|abbr=on}} beneath Earth's surface. The transition between the inner core and outer core is located approximately {{convert|5150|km|mi|abbr=on}} beneath the Earth's surface. Unlike the inner core, the outer core is liquid. The inner core is also referred to as the solid core.<ref>Beno Gutenberg (4 June 2016). Physics of the Earth's Interior. Elsevier. pp. 115–. {{ISBN|978-1-4832-8212-1}}.</ref>

==Properties==
Seismic inversions of [[Seismic wave#Body waves|body waves]] and [[Seismic wave#Free oscillations of the Earth|normal modes]] constrain the radius of the outer core to be 3483&nbsp;km with an uncertainty of 5&nbsp;km, while that of the inner core is 1220±10&nbsp;km.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Ahrens|editor-first1=Thomas J.|title=Global earth physics a handbook of physical constants|date=1995|publisher=[[American Geophysical Union]]|location=Washington, DC|isbn=9780875908519|edition=3rd}}</ref>{{rp|94}}

Estimates for the temperature of the outer core are about {{convert|3000|–|4500|K|abbr=on}} in its outer regions and {{convert|4000|–|8000|K|abbr=on}} near the inner core.<ref name="DeWijs98">{{cite journal |title=The viscosity of liquid iron at the physical conditions of the Earth's core |doi=10.1038/33905 |url=http://www.homepages.ucl.ac.uk/~ucfbdxa/pubblicazioni/nat.pdf |volume=392 |issue=6678 |year=1998 |last1=De Wijs |first1=Gilles A. |last2=Kresse |first2=Georg |last3=Vočadlo |first3=Lidunka |last4=Dobson |first4=David |last5=Alfè |first5=Dario |last6=Gillan |first6=Michael J. |last7=Price |first7=Geoffrey D. |journal=Nature |pages=805 |bibcode=1998Natur.392..805D}}</ref> Evidence for a fluid outer core includes  from [[seismology]] which shows that [[Seismic wave|seismic]] [[S-wave|shear-waves]] are not transmitted through the outer core<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jeffreys|first=Harold|date=1926-06-01|title=The Rigidity of the Earth's Central Core.|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1365-246X.1926.tb05385.x/abstract|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|language=en|volume=1|issue=|pages=371–383|doi=10.1111/j.1365-246X.1926.tb05385.x|issn=1365-246X|pmid=|access-date=|via=|bibcode=1926GeoJ....1..371J}}</ref> Because of its high temperature, modeling work has shown that the outer core is a low [[viscosity]] fluid that convects [[turbulence|turbulently]].<ref name="DeWijs98" /> [[Eddy current]]s in the nickel iron [[fluid]] of the outer core are believed to influence the [[Earth's magnetic field]]. The average [[magnetic field]] strength in the Earth's outer core was measured to be 2.5 [[millitesla]], 50 times stronger than the magnetic field at the surface.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff writer |title=First Measurement Of Magnetic Field Inside Earth's Core |url=http://www.science20.com/news_articles/first_measurement_magnetic_field_inside_earths_core |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=Science 2.0 |date=17 December 2010 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature09643 |title=Tidal dissipation and the strength of the Earth's internal magnetic field |year=2010 |last1=Buffett |first1=Bruce A. |journal=Nature |volume=468 |issue=7326 |pages=952–4 |pmid=21164483 |bibcode=2010Natur.468..952B}}</ref> The outer core is not under enough pressure to be solid, so it is liquid even though it has a composition similar to the inner core. [[Sulfur]] and [[oxygen]] could be present in the outer core.<ref name=nature473_361>{{cite journal |first1=David |last1=Gubbins |first2=Binod |last2=Sreenivasan |first3=Jon |last3=Mound |first4=Sebastian |last4=Rost |title=Melting of the Earth's inner core |journal=Nature |volume=473 |pages=361–363 |date=May 19, 2011 |doi=10.1038/nature10068 |issue=7347 |pmid=21593868 |bibcode=2011Natur.473..361G}}</ref>

As heat is transferred outward toward the [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]], the net trend is for the inner boundary of the liquid region to freeze, causing the solid inner core to grow. This growth rate is estimated to be 1&nbsp;mm per year.<ref name=ng4_264>{{cite journal |title=Reconciling the hemispherical structure of Earth's inner core with its super-rotation |first1=Lauren |last1=Waszek |first2=Jessica |last2=Irving |last3=Deuss |first3=Arwen |journal=Nature Geoscience |volume=4 |pages=264–267 |year=2011 |doi=10.1038/ngeo1083|bibcode=2011NatGe...4..264W }}</ref>

