{{short description|Attempt in the early 1960s to drill through the Earth's crust into the Mohorovičić discontinuity,}} {{redirect|Mohole|text=Moholes also feature in the [[Mars trilogy]] as fictional terraforming devices}} {{refimprove section|date=May 2009}} {{Infobox historical event |Event_Name = Project Mohole |Image_Name = Mohopix-3.gif |Imagesize = 250 |Image_Alt = |Image_Caption = One of the six submerged buoys used for dynamic positioning in Project Mohole. They were lowered to about 200 feet into a circular pattern. The ''CUSS I'' would then use sonar to manoeuvre itself in the centre of that circle. |Thumb_Time = |AKA = |Participants = |Location = Off [[Guadalupe Island]], [[Mexico]], [[Pacific Ocean]] |Date = 1961 |nongregorian = |Deaths = |Result = Failed attempt to enter the [[Mohorovičić discontinuity]] |URL = }}
'''Project Mohole''' was an ambitious attempt in the early 1960s to drill through the Earth's [[Crust (geology)|crust]] into the [[Mohorovičić discontinuity]], and to provide an Earth science complement to the high-profile [[Space Race]]. The project was initially led by the [[American Miscellaneous Society]] with funding from the [[National Science Foundation]].
== History == [[File:Mohopix-1.gif|thumb|200px|''CUSS I'']]
Phase One was executed in spring 1961. Five holes were drilled off the coast of [[Guadalupe Island]], [[Mexico]], the deepest to {{convert|601|ft|abbr=on}} below the sea floor in {{convert|11700|ft|abbr=on}} of water. This was unprecedented: not in the hole's depth but because of the depth of the ocean and because it was drilled from an untethered platform. Also, the [[core sample]] proved to be valuable, penetrating through [[Miocene]]-age sediments for the first time to reveal the lowest 13&nbsp;m (44&nbsp;ft) consisting of [[basalt]].
Project Mohole contracted with Global Marine of Los Angeles for the use of its oil drillship ''CUSS I''. A consortium of [[Continental Oil Company|Continental]], [[Union Oil Company|Union]], [[Superior Oil Company|Superior]] and [[Shell Oil Company|Shell]] Oil Companies, CUSS had originally developed it in 1956 as a technological test bed for the nascent [[offshore oil industry]]. ''CUSS I'' was one of the first vessels in the world capable of drilling in water depth up to {{convert|11700|ft|abbr=on}}, while maintaining a position within a radius of {{convert|600|ft|m|abbr=on}}. Project Mohole expanded its operational range by inventing what is now known as [[dynamic positioning]].<ref name="Van Keuren">{{cite book|last=Van Keuren|first=David K.|title=The Machine in Neptune's Garden: Historical Perspectives on Technology and the Marine Environment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fj0sCBGo1DEC&pg=PA191&lpg=PA191&dq=Global+Marine+of+Los+Angeles+CUSS+I&source=bl&ots=_sKeXA0Kqb&sig=vufDicL8pqzQy2n7zMlBL2x6QCc&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NYEXU_eNCcnClQWC5oHICg&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Global%20Marine%20of%20Los%20Angeles%20CUSS%20I&f=false|accessdate=1 March 2014|publisher=Science History Publications|date=2004|isbn=0881353728|pages=183–210|chapter=Chapter 6: Breaking New Ground-The Origins of Scientific Ocean Drilling}}</ref>
Phase One proved that both the technology and expertise were available to drill into the [[Earth's mantle]]. It was intended as the experimental phase of the project, and did succeed in drilling to a depth of 601 feet below the sea floor.<ref name=natac>{{citation|title=Project Mohole, 1958-1966|publisher=National Academies|url=http://www.nationalacademies.org/history/mohole/|accessdate=2011-04-22}}</ref><ref name="IODP">{{cite web|url=http://www.iodp.org/project-mohole|title=Project Mohole|publisher=[[International Ocean Discovery Program|IODP]]|accessdate=5 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306005146/http://www.iodp.org/project-mohole|archivedate = 6 March 2014 }}</ref> However, deeper drilling never took place. An attempted shift of operational control to the National Science Foundation proved unsatisfactory, and in short order the American Miscellaneous Society dissolved itself, Phase Two of the project was abandoned and the entire project was discontinued by Congress, which objected to increasing costs in 1966.<ref name=natac /><ref name="IODP"/>
