{{Infobox mineral | name = Tugarinovite | boxwidth = | boxbgcolor = | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | category = [[Oxide mineral]] | formula = MoO<sub>2</sub> | strunz = 4.DB.05 | dana = | system = Monoclinic | class = | symmetry = Monoclinic - prismatic [[H-M symbol]] (2/m) [[Space group]]: P 21/n | unit cell = a = 5.6 Å, b = 4.85 Å, c = 5.53 Å; β = 119.37° | color = Dark lilac-brown | habit = Crystals are tabular striated prisms | twinning = Polysynthetic | cleavage = | fracture = | tenacity = | mohs = 4.6 | luster = Greasy to metallic | streak = Greenish gray | diaphaneity = Semitransparent | gravity = 6.58 (calculated) | density = | polish = | opticalprop = Biaxial | refractive = | birefringence = | pleochroism = Light gray to dark pink; pale yellow to bluish olive-brown in reflected light | 2V = | dispersion = | extinction = | length fast/slow = | fluorescence = | absorption = | melt = | fusibility = | diagnostic = | solubility = | impurities = | alteration = | other = | prop1 = | prop1text = | references = <ref name=HBM>[http://www.handbookofmineralogy.com/pdfs/tugarinovite.pdf Handbook of Mineralogy]</ref> <ref name=Mindat>[https://www.mindat.org/min-4043.html Tugarinovite on Mindat.org]</ref><ref name=Webmin>[http://webmineral.com/data/Tugarinovite.shtml#.WPKok4jytPY Tugarinovite on Webmin]</ref> }} '''Tugarinovite''' is a rare [[molybdenum]] [[oxide mineral]] with formula MoO<sub>2</sub>. It occurs as a primary mineral phase associated with [[metasomatism]] in a [[sulfur]] deficient [[Redox|reducing]] environment. In the [[Type locality (geology)|type locality]] it occurs with [[uraninite]], [[molybdenite]], [[galena]], [[zircon]] and [[wulfenite]].<ref name=HBM/>
Tugarinovite was first described for an occurrence in the Lenskoye molybdenum–uranium deposit in the [[Amur Oblast|Amurskaya Oblast]], [[Russian Far East|Far-Eastern Region]], [[Russia]]. It was named for geochemist Ivan Alekseevich Tugarinov of the Vernadskii Institute in Moscow.<ref name=HBM/><ref name=Mindat/> In addition to its type locality in Russia it has been reported from the [[Allende meteorite]] in [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]], [[Mexico]], the [[Ryukyu Islands|Nansei Archipelago]] of [[Japan]] and [[Bohemia]] in the [[Czech Republic]].<ref name=Mindat/>
